We recommended that Management:
16. Expedite the process of hiring and filling the position of Municipal Assessor;
17. Coordinate with and seek technical assistance from the Provincial Assessor and/or the DOF-Bureau of Local Government Finance to fast-track the preparation of the updated SMVs of the Municipality and cause the drafting of an Ordinance for consideration of the Sanggunian, incorporating therein the proposed SMV, assessment level and tax rate to support the conduct of GRRPA within the reglementary period;
18. Augment the number of qualified personnel assigned at the Municipal Assessor’s Office to meet the minimum personnel requirements stipulated in the MRPAAO and conduct capacity-building interventions to facilitate the conduct of the general revision of real property assessments in adherence to Section 219 of the same Code and DILG-DOF JMC No. 2010-001, and closely monitor its completion; and
19. Make representation with the Local Chief Executive/Local Sanggunian to appropriate funds for the computerization of the assessment records to speed up the completion of GRRPA data gathering and encoding.

We recommended and the Management agreed to observe the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances to have reliable PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability as follows:
1. Issue an Office Order to create/reconstitute the Inventory Committee, as some have already retired from service;
2. Submit the approved PIP to the COA Audit Team within the prescribed period;
3. Adopt the uniform numbering system for property numbers of PPE and require the Property Unit to update the property stickers based on the prescribed format and to include the required information under Section 5.6 and 5.7 of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and
4. Strictly follow the guidelines and procedures in the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items and require the Accountant and Property Officer to reconcile their records based on the results of the actual physical inventory and effect necessary adjustments.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to indicating the pertinent information such as the date when the fund was received, the source agency, the purpose, and the amount received, utilized, and liquidated;
6. Ensure that fund transfers recorded under the Trust Fund are duly supported by a MOA; and
7. Return the excess funds for the fully implemented/completed PDAF and other long-outstanding projects amounting to ₱431,908.13 to the respective Source Agencies and the PDAF amounting to ₱2,588,266.70 to the Bureau of Treasury.

We recommended that the LDRRMO coordinate with the OCD on the preparation and submission of the Municipality’s PSCP pursuant to NDRRMC Memorandum No 33, s. 2018.
34. We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
A. To conduct a risk assessment;
B. To identify critical processes and functions;
C. To determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
D. To conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
E. To formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and the related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed templates and requirements in the PSCP guidebook; and
F. To submit a plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the Local Chief Executive for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.

